## Migration Workflow

This is the correct flow: make changes locally → generate migration → test → push to remote.

### Step 1 — Make schema changes in local Studio
```
Open: http://127.0.0.1:54323
Use Table Editor or SQL Editor to make changes to your local DB
```

### Step 2 — Generate migration from the diff
```bash
# Compare local DB to migration history → generate SQL migration file
supabase db diff -f add_orders_table
# Creates: supabase/migrations/[timestamp]_add_orders_table.sql
# Review this file carefully before pushing
```

### Step 3 — Test locally
```bash
# Reset local DB and replay all migrations from scratch
supabase db reset
# This is safe locally — nukes and rebuilds
# Confirms migrations are idempotent and in correct order
```

### Step 4 — Push to remote
```bash
# Apply all pending migrations to remote Supabase project
supabase db push
# Shows which migrations will run → confirms → applies
```

### Manual migration (write SQL directly)
```bash
# Create empty migration file
supabase migration new add_pgvector_index
# Edit: supabase/migrations/[timestamp]_add_pgvector_index.sql

# Then push:
supabase db push
```

